css mario, squishy buttons, and genuary begins view this issue on codepen css mario, squishy buttons, and genuary begins happy new year! this week's codepen community highlights include a trip to super mario world with cutting-edge css animations from temani afif, a stupendously tactile button from voicu apostol, and the kickoff of the annual generative coding challenge, genuary. plus, adam argyle shows us how to fix the "irradiation illusion" with css, and konstantin denerz uses css shape() to pay tribute to the commodore 64. pen jelly squish button you're gonna need to set aside a little time to squish this thing. either drag your cursor vertically, or click the "follow mouse" checkbox to connect the squish to your mouse movements for this button with jelly inside from voicu apostol. pen css-only mario world (with keyboard!) temani afif combines animation-timeline , animation-range , and container scroll-state queries for a side-scrolling adventure, mario style! chrome only for now. collection #codepenchallenge: until next year our collection from the final week of the 2025 codepen challenges includes pens by matt cannon , vanessa victorino , chris bolson , and alexandre vacassin . ready to join the 2026 codepen challenge community? the january challenge is on ğŸ’ª pen text frame border animation rotation a text marquee traces the edges of a blobby photo in this slick css & svg animation from fernando cohen. check out what happens when you hover the photo, and take a gander at fernando's earlier iteration from 2022, too. link using css to fix the irradiation illusion "ever noticed how white text on a black background looks thicker than black text on a white background, even though the weights are the same? this post teaches you how to account for this and adjust perceived font weight for dark mode without layout shift, with variable fonts and the grad axis." an excellent tutorial with embedded pens from adam argyle. sponsor go make something awesome! web awesome is a massive library of meticulously crafted, standards-based ui components that work in any framework. built by the team behind font awesome. start for free today, or go pro for premium components and services at 20% off for a limited time. link directional css with scroll-state(scrolled) speaking of scroll states, una kravets gives us the scoop on the new scrolled value for scroll-state() queries in this tutorial with helpful embedded pen demos. pen genuary 2026 genuary 2026 is happening now! alexander korotaev answered day 3's "fibonacci forever" with this lysergic javascript animation. check out fractalkitty's take on the same prompt , too. pen svg fireworks loop "a fluid fireworks animation based on a dribbble shot by lizzie hamblin. as a react component, the animation consists of child components for individual fireworks, which makes it easy to configure." from jon kantner. pen c64 logo (css shape() ) konstantin denerz uses some very new tech (css clip-path: shape() ) to pay tribute to some very old tech (the commodore 64 , from 1982). chrisâ€™ corner a collection of web design and development news and thoughts from codepen's own chris coyier. freshly-fallen css first corner of the new year, so, ya know: âœºâ—Ÿ(ï¼¾ âˆ‡ ï¼¾)â—âœº i feel like we should do css for this one. itâ€™s easily my favorite technology thing and basically bffs with the spirit of codepen. in brand-spanking-new news (gnu neues?) the whole â€œmasonryâ€ saga is starting to come to a close. the naming is (drumroll please): .container { display: grid-lanes; grid-template-columns: repeat( auto-fill, minmax(250px, 1fr)); gap: 16px; } i like it. lanes. like youâ€™re playing a driving video game or something. the webkit gang has the story , and theyâ€™ve got demos ready. try out grid lanes in safari technology preview 234! all of the demos at webkit.org/demos/grid3 have been updated with the new syntax, including other use cases for grid lanes. iâ€™d credit david desandro for the name â€œmasonryâ€, which is certainly a lot more stuck in peopleâ€™s heads. heâ€™s understandably disappointed in the new name. i canâ€™t get past the idea that a brick wall (the â€œmasonryâ€ connection) doesnâ€™t look like this looks (itâ€™s wrong by 90 degrees). so color me a fan of the new naming. in the â€œi had no idea this was comingâ€ category is text-grow and text-shrink . iâ€™ve probably used dave rupertâ€™s (ancient) fittext more times than i can count in my career. first, viewport units kinda obsoleted it, but that required magic numbers to get just right. now itâ€™s going toâ€¦ just work? although i think itâ€™s just a prototype so far. ( via adam ) h1 { text-grow: per-line scale; } see the gif and another entry in the â€œi had no idea this was comingâ€ is scroll-triggered animations . iâ€™m very aware of scroll- driven animations and find that whole api extremely cool, but this is something else. normally when you apply an animation it just runs immediately when the page loads, possibly with a manual delay. with the driven animations you can attach it to a timeline based on the scroll progress of an element or the position related to the viewport. with this, you can also have it triggered instead. a trigger is a custom ident like: animation: my-animation 0.5s; animation-trigger: --thing-in-view play-forwards; then you create that trigger: timeline-trigger-name: --thing-in-view; timeline-trigger-source: view(); which could be the same or a different element. cool. i obviously love that there is a bunch of demos in a collection . i was aware of (newly) customizable selects and iâ€™ve had my own plays with it , but brecht de ruyte is the master. iâ€™ll link up part 4 of his so-far-five-part series on the matter. this is whatâ€™s happening: see gif like: whaaaaat. but i suppose i could have guessed. at one time css gave us a :checked selector and html has labels-connected-to-inputs and people used those things to build absolutely amazing things . there is much more interactivity on offer in a <select> . you can adjust your email preferences any time, or instantly opt out of emails of this kind. need help with anything? hit up support . interested in sponsoring? here's our sponsorship info .

building a machine learning platform - the trendyol way trendyol newsletter yazan: trendyol group yazan: trendyol group sohbete katÄ±lmak iÃ§in linkedinâ€™deki bu makaleyi okuyun linkedinâ€˜de oku ~mjr0rpcp~3d-null-null&eid=flpa7u-mjr0rpcp-3d&otptoken=mwiwmtfkztqxnjjhy2jjnwjjmjqwngvkndaxowu3yjq4ymnkzdu0njlmywm4ytyxnzljnta4nmu0zjvhntrmmwy3zdrkzmiwnjdjzgmxody3zwzlztg0nwrjymfiyzu0odgzodhlmgnmogzkywyxytc5mgi3yiwxlde%3d trendyol tech newsletter no:2 welcome to a new edition of the trendyol tech newsletter. this month, we take a closer look at building a machine learning platform, the trendyol way. beyond theory, beyond architecture slidesâ€”this is how our teams design, operate, and evolve an ml platform that supports hundreds of real-world use cases across trendyol tech. from infrastructure decisions to platform capabilities and trade-offs, this edition is a hands-on look at what it actually takes to run machine learning systems in production. if youâ€™re curious about how ml platforms look beyond diagramsâ€”and how they actually operate in real lifeâ€”youâ€™re in the right place. letâ€™s get into the details. what is a machine learning platform and why are we building it? the tech world has been creating machine learning products for a while. at trendyol, we generate value from ml products within wide-range e-commerce domains including but not limited to personalization, recommendation, forecasting, fraud, computer vision, logistic optimizations etc. industry best practices and well known tools have gotten us so far but trendyol scale - wide range of domains, limitless iterations, aggressive agility, high throughput, petabytes of data - required tailor made solutions. to cover the need, we are developing ml platform to provide our colleagues with toolsets for feature engineering, experimentation and inference needs. our fundamental approach aims to decrease cognitive load coming from technical obstacles and create more focus on business applications. our way of building the ml systems our understanding of platform efforts consists of three main categories: enablement: taking teams and projects from 0 to 1 by introducing domains with ml capabilities. acceleration: going from 1 to 100 with rapid iterations, addressing and removing bottlenecks. optimization: making 100 more effective, reliable and maintainable. these efforts include both platform tools and ways of working definitions. a typical ml project is executed by data scientists and engineers. they create value by implementing and iterating a project lifecycle and ml platform team and tools are meant to support them at every step in this lifecycle. the image below summarizes an ideal ml project lifecycle from a high level point of view. letâ€™s deep dive into the steps one by one! ideation and preparation each ml project begins with an idea - a problem, model or feature. to experiment with an idea, a data scientist needs a development environment and related toolset to play with data and algorithms. our main analytical data storage solutions are bigquery and gcs buckets which are the beginning points for almost every project where the data is collected through our data engineering and data platform teams. the next part is a development environment that ml platform provides. these environments come with main ingredients - jupyter notebook, computation power, compatible drivers and libraries of choice, a disk for local storage, connection with shared file systems etc. data is available and the environment is up and running, the data scientist now can conduct explanatory data analysis, feature experiments, model trials and evaluations. from a platform point of view, one of the most challenging parts of this step is to provide computation power in a reliable and optimized way. we utilize kubeflow notebooks for this purpose. users can select memory, cpu, disk and gpu specs according to their needs. we provide various options preconfigured docker images for popular libraries like tensorflow and pytorch can be selected when creating environments to get to work rapidly. dependencies and versions are configured and tested by the ml platform team to achieve maximum reliability possible. how do we optimize usage and keep costs under control for environments? it is a whole other story to tell, look out for upcoming articles. model training once the preparations are done, it is time for the actual model training. the data scientist decided on the features and the algorithm to experiment on at this point. feature engineering with a sample data set is straightforward but when you are to train a model with real data, features become harder to calculate. in fact, feature engineering typically consumes the largest chunk of a data scientistâ€™s time. creating reliable, scalable, and point-in-time correct features for production is a different beast. to bridge the gap between raw data and ml models, we built our internal feature store solution: panama. it acts as the centralized refinery where raw "ore" (data) is transformed into "gold" (features) through authorized pipelines. beyond just technical abstraction, it tries to solve critical challenges: it drastically reduces the time and effort required to create models, maximizes feature reusability across teams, standardizes feature definitions, and ultimately improves consistency and data quality. our architecture is designed to support both high-volume batch processing and low-latency streaming needs without compromising on scale. for batch processing, we ingest large-scale data from our data warehouse or ssdp (trendyolâ€™s self service data platform) data products, processing them via sql transformations orchestrated by cloud composer. on the streaming front, we consume real-time events from kafka and utilize apache flink to process and convert them into features instantly. a valuable capability we unlocked here is generating training data directly from these streaming sources; after computation with flink, we store this training data in iceberg format, registered in the bigquery metastore. currently hosting 1,350 batches and 50 streaming feature groups, our feature store utilizes both offline and online storage layers. we use bigquery as our offline store, managing over 700 tb of data; and to offer flexibility, features can also be exported directly from bigquery to gcs. for the online store, which is optimized for high-speed, low-latency access, we rely on couchbase. it accommodates 12 tb of data, ensuring that our models always have the data they need, the moment they need it. to serve batch features in this online store, we use cloud dataproc to handle the ingestion and synchronization process efficiently. from a developer experience perspective, a data scientist defines a feature group using a yaml-based contract file. this contract includes metadata (owners, descriptions), time granularity, and specific feature logic. once a feature is defined, the platform handles the rest, making the feature available via our api and python sdk without any further manual intervention. after features are created and available from the feature store, the algorithm can be executed by ingesting those features. while training, we ensure that only anonymized data is utilized in compliance with kvkk (personal data protection law) and gdpr requirements, adhering strictly to the boundaries of user consent. some model training efforts may require advanced data ingestion strategies, especially when you are dealing with unstructured data. we utilize parallel file systems to solve small file problems occurring during such cases to accelerate data ingestions. a related article can be found at the link the same notebook from the development environment can also be used for executing trainings. environments give enough computation power for most of the cases however some deep learning cases may require more. our flex jobs module addresses those needs. flex jobs utilizes kueue with gcpâ€™s dws system to provide data scientists with gpus such as a100, h100 and h200. our standard approach suggests extracting a training output as an artifact. any format is acceptable - a json, pickle or onnx runtime. this is because model management is an essential part of the lifecycle. our model management system consists of a registry backed by gcs buckets, a versioning system, a model card for metadata and key metrics definitions and special tags for further usage. the model card also holds experiment tracking integration for mlflow experiments. in this sense the model card is a record store for our experiments and models, acts as the source of truth for contracts between stakeholders and reliable storage for our artifacts. test and evaluation training can be executed multiple times with different parameters, configs, features to achieve accuracy or kpi goals. experiment tracking tools help data scientists to benchmark their executions. our model card module introduces a simple storage for this purpose. powerful tools like mlflow or weights&biases also give much more insights for accuracy metrics. certain domains cannot define accuracy only with prepared data. our data scientist colleagues run business kpi simulations on sample data from production systems for those domains. as we get closer to the production, each change introduced - pre/post process codes, inference servers, quantizations or caches - requires reassessment of the model. nobody got time for that repeating process. our pipeline solution, piper, introduces pythonic components to automate any part of the lifecycle. whether it is an offline prediction or an evaluation pipeline, our colleagues can implement their needs easily with the component library that piper provides. online and offline serving now we are confident that our model will work. there are two main ways to use it in production, batch prediction and live inference. batch predictions run periodically or as one-off jobs. our flex jobs or airflow jobs backed by ml platform jobs infrastructure are currently popular options in our organization. ingest features as a batch from our offline store, feed them to your model and process the output - easy and effective. batch predictions cover the majority of our business needs for now. live inference, however, is more tricky. ideal deployment pipeline consists of verification of the model artifact, applying inference server of choice and our best practices for their configuration, deployment configurations for domain needs and a smoke test to ensure successful deployment. runtime requirements differ much according to business domains. piper has inference components for all of them. low traffic models: python services for prediction scripts that can be consumed with http requests or kafka events. deployments are triggered through our developer platform, tbp (trendyol builder platform). high throughput models: distributed and auto scaled predictions using ray serve. model response times are not so critical for those. low latency models: nvidia triton deployments with grpc services and istio load balancing with the advancements in piper, we managed to automate the model deployment pipeline but there are still uncovered areas. especially for low latency models, our way of working suggests defining traffic and latency needs from model cards. with the essential information in hand, ml platform team provides support for optimizing live inference services manually. this approach aims to ensure the reliability of high throughput - low latency customer faced products. optimization step is the time when we decide whether a model can be run on cpus or we should use gpus for optimal performance. we have 130+ gpus operating within our data centers for now - a100, h100 and h200 of type. priority usage of them is reserved for low latency customer faced models within our standards. live inference challenges are not limited to models but also requires an advanced approach for our online feature store. handling thousands of requests per minute, our online store faces intense read pressure that can lead to data hotspots, threatening both performance and scalability. to counter this, we developed a data service api that utilizes a consistent hashing algorithm. with this strategy, we route identical requests to the specific kubernetes pod, allowing us to consolidate duplicate queries into a single execution queue. following a cache-first logic, the system checks memory first; data is returned instantly upon a cache hit, and couchbase is queried only on a miss. this architecture drastically reduces redundant database trips, alleviates strain on the couchbase cluster, and maximizes overall system efficiency. another serving solution that ml platform offers is for ai models, llms or vlms. piper has components also for serving models with vllm, sglang and lmdeploy. we deploy both internal and open source models through them and enable our organization to utilize ai capabilities. those models are behind a genai gateway implementation developed by extending litellm answering our enterprise needs. until now, we integrated 50 internal and external models to the system. monitoring voila! you are in production. butâ€¦ after all, a model is successful as long as it meets our business needs. common practice to assess that within our organization is to conduct a/b tests. domains check for business metrics with those tests through our experimentation platform, janus, and decide whether the model is champion or needs another iteration. another way of deciding a champion model is production accuracy results. usage cost is the driver of roi decisions. resource allocation and utilization metrics are transparent for company resources. we are working on detecting data and model drift at scale. and of course, there are dashboards, alarms and logs for throughput, response time and error rate for inference services through our monitoring platform, beholder. an ml platform is a developer experience product in the end. we produce lifecycle metrics through analytics from usage of our products. improving business kpis through agility is our main goal. at scale even 1% uplift is enough to celebrate an iteration and we are trying to achieve hundreds of them. a good example of that is the collaborative efforts of search data science, search relevancy and ml platform teams. within one year, search algorithms have been iterated 100+ times with 50% champion rate. those systems received ~1m rpm throughput and features are queried with ~6m rpm during peak times of the november campaigns period. future ahead right now, we are working on expanding the capabilities of piper to enable more pipelines and automations. manual steps are to be automated to achieve acceleration for all steps of the continuous lifecycle. a smooth data experience is critical when you operate on trendyol scale. not just creating and scaling, but also monitoring and reliability - data quality, drift detection, pipeline automations, retention and recreation. we are collaborating with our colleagues from the data management tribe to provide data scientists and ml engineers with those abilities. we embedded creating and presenting real life case studies to our own development lifecycle, as one of the most crucial parts of developing a platform is technical documentation and example guides. live inference optimizations for achieving response time or throughput slas are still done manually and must be automated. we are trying to standardize our efforts and make those automations generally available though piper. costly and limited computation resources should be allocated in a business effective and smart way - autoscale up and down with dynamic hybrid allocation. should we keep letting gpus be idle when they are under much less load during night time? feature storage and serving needs a different approach from application databases. agility in data storage must be achieved from database infra to developer experience point of view. can we create a versatile database system specifically for online feature stores? we are expanding our toolset for the ai era. generic models - llms and vlms should be easily accessible, reliable and scalable - of course with cost optimizations. does every solution require generic llms or can we manage a fleet of business specific ai models by enabling domains more? stay tuned for answers! that wraps up this deep dive into how we build and run our machine learning platform at trendyol tech. as always, weâ€™re curious about what you want to explore next. which technical topics should we break down? what challenges are you tackling? which teams or systems would you like to hear from? your input helps shape future editionsâ€”so donâ€™t hold back. ğŸ”— share your thoughts, questions, or requests here and if building platforms at scale, working with real-world ml systems, and solving meaningful problems sounds like your kind of work, you might want to take a look at our open roles. ğŸ”— view all open roles: finally, a big thank you to the team behind this edition. strong platforms donâ€™t build this article was written by jeff dean, chief scientist, demis hassabis, ceo google deepmind and james manyika, svp research, labs, technology & society. 2025 has been a year of extraordinary progress in research. with artificial intelligence, we can see its trajectory shifting from a tool to a utility: from something people use to something they can put to work. if 2024 was about laying the multimodal foundations for this era, 2025 was the year ai began to really think, act and explore the world alongside us. with quantum computing, we made progress towards real-world applications. and across the board, we helped turn research into reality, with more capable and useful products and tools making a positive impact on people's lives today. hereâ€™s a look back at some of the breakthroughs, products and scientific milestones that defined the work of google, google deepmind and google research in a year of relentless progress. delivering breakthroughs on world-class models this year, we significantly advanced our model capabilities with breakthroughs on reasoning, multimodal understanding, model efficiency, and generative capabilities, beginning with the release of gemini 2.5 in march and culminating in the november launch of gemini 3 and the december launch of gemini 3 flash. built on a foundation of state-of-the-art reasoning, gemini 3 pro is our most powerful model to date, designed to help you bring any idea to life. it topped the lmarena leaderboard and redefined multimodal reasoning with breakthrough scores on benchmarks like humanityâ€™s last exam â€” state-of-the-art of 23.4% on matharena apex. we followed shortly with gemini 3 flash, which combines gemini 3's pro-grade reasoning with flash-level latency, efficiency and cost, making it the most performant model for its size. gemini 3 flash's quality surpasses our previous gemini 2.5 pro-scale model's capabilities at a fraction of the price and substantially better latency, continuing our gemini-era trend of 'the next generation's flash model is better than the previous generation's pro model'. learn more about our progress on our world-class ai models this year: gemini 3 flash: reading through our collective memory of 2025 a year of hope and worry (issue #409) reading through our collective memory of 2025 a year of hope and worry (issue #409) by the medium blog ( âˆ™ december 26, 2025 âˆ™ 2 min read âˆ™ view on medium ( one of the pleasures of december is the chance to look back and reflect on the year. from data-driven lists to vulnerable personal essays, year-end roundups offer a way to take stock of what mattered. despite a year defined by personal upheaval - losing a long-held job, separating from a long-term partner, and starting a new business in a chaotic market - joe foster ( 's year-end reflection includes how he kept a long-promised commitment to write ( , publishing 22 medium pieces and making steady progress on his novel. writing from her position in developer relations at google's ui toolkit flutter ( , emma twersky ( tracks 2025's ten highlights ( , from speed improvements like impeller to new ai features like mcp servers and genui, plus a peek at 2026 plans. designer tom whitwell ( is back with his annual list of 52 things he learned ( over the course of the year, such as the rapid decline in global deaths from air pollution, falling murder rates in london, and the strange fact that robot hands need fingernails. for nasa columnist ethan siegel ( , 2025 marked a year when distrust eclipsed well-established science. he revisits ten established scientific truths ( - including climate change, vaccination efficacy, and covid's zoonotic origins - that nonetheless became unpopular this year. meanwhile, wikimedia ( published its most-read english wikipedia articles of 2025 ( , topped by entries on charlie kirk, ed gein, donald trump, and pope leo xiv. others chose to share their favorite media. cory doctorow ( tracked 2025 through his reading list ( , from nonfiction about facebook's executive ranks ( to science fiction about ai surveillance ( . barack obama ( likewise compiled his 2025 favorites ( , from books like jill lepore's history of the u.s. constitution ( , to film adaptations like hamnet, to orchestral pop like rosalÃ­a ( . adam sharman ( documented 2025 through gaming ( , ranking not new releases but the games he played this year for the first time - 2024's pacific drive takes the number-one spot for its atmosphere and how the car itself becomes a trusted companion. if you're still figuring out what this year meant to you, check out the 2025 ( and year-in-review ( tags on medium to see new stories on this theme as they're published. - anna dorn ( a quote to end the year on "whether we tip toward golden age or prolonged crisis depends on choices we make now." - rita mcgrath ( on moving forward in 2026 by examining how 2025 offered both hope and worry ( . the easiest mistake to avoid early edip, here is a mistake that quietly kills progress early on. trying to do everything at the same time. product research. store design. copywriting. logistics. marketing. it feels productive, but it creates confusion. progress comes faster when you sequence things, not stack them. here is the correct order for beginners: first: structure you need a store that works technically and visually. without this, nothing else matters. second: product feedback you learn what works by watching how people react, not by guessing. third: small improvements change one thing at a time. image, price, or headline. then observe again. most beginners reverse this order. they try to optimize before anything exists. that is why starting with a ready made store helps so much. it locks in step one so you can focus on step two and three. a tradelle ready made store gives you that starting point: âœ… prebuilt shopify store (launch ready) âœ… 20 products with proven demand and margins âœ… automated fulfillment with 6â€“10 day delivery âœ… expert review before you go live âœ… 304â€‘step growth checklist âœ… 30â€‘day moneyâ€‘back guarantee ğŸ‘‰ claim your ready-made store clarity comes from order, not effort. best, christian team tradelle tradelle ltd, 71-75 shelton street, covent garden, london, wc2h 9jq , uk company number: 14462289 unsubscribe

the monthly build - google developer program - december 2025 google developer program builder spotlight: gemini 3 flash is here the gemini 3 family just got faster. gemini 3 flash is now available in preview. it combines the reasoning capabilities of gemini 3 pro with flash-level latency, making it our most capable model for agentic workflows. it outperforms 2.5 pro while being 3x faster and using 30% fewer tokens for complex reasoning tasks. it is available today in google ai studio, gemini cli, vertex ai, and is the default model for our new agentic platform, google antigravity. read the full lambda loop newsletter - december 2025 lambda ( ) monthly newsletter 2025 is coming to an end: itâ€™s time to close the (lambda) loop. in this final edition of the year, use our guide to deploy the brand new nvidia nemotron 3 nano and get access to more affordable nvidia hgx b200 instances. explore insights from a fantastic time with the ai community at neurips and from yet another massive achievement in the arc prize. finally, the learners will be pleased: hear from the authors of five published papers and level up on critical ai infrastructure such as multi-cloud, co-packaged optics (cpo), and deployments of large-scale ai factories. spotlight / nvidia nemotron 3 nano how-to ( ) nvidia releases nemotron 3 nano fast, simple, and production-ready. nemotron 3 nano is the first of three in the nemotron 3 family. run it on lambda ( ) b200 ( ) nvidia hgx b200 instances now available in 1x, 2x, 4x, and 8x sizes with 180 gb of hbm3e memory and fp8/fp4 capabilities, get full nvidia hgx b200 performance for pre-training, fine-tuning, and inference without reserving excess resources. b200 instances are now available in 1x, 2x, 4x, or 8x configurations, so you only consume the gpu capacity you need. launch now ( ) hot off the command line / neurips recap ( ) what neurips 2025 tells us about progress from bigger models to better intelligence: in his latest piece, chuan li, lambdaâ€™s chief scientific officer, unpacks where the field is heading. learn more ( ) architects2025 ( ) the architects secure runner-up in arc prize 2025 last year, â€œthe architects,â€ a lambda-sponsored team (including lambda researcher david hartmann), won the arc prize 2024. this year, they finished second out of 1,400+ teams with a final leaderboard score of 16.53%. learn more ( ) lambda multi-cloud blog ( ) a blueprint for running training and inference reliably across multiple clouds multi-cloud isnâ€™t a strategy so much as an outcome of constraints. gpus are scarce, dc capacity is tight, and egress fees complicate moving training data. learn more ( ) nvidia cpo blog ( ) silicon photonics for ai clusters: performance, scale, reliability, and efficiency cpo reduces latency, improves power efficiency by 3.5Ã—, and increases network reliability by 10Ã— at scale. this means faster training, steadier long runs, and reliable scaling toward 100k+ gpu clusters. learn more ( ) knowledge drop / a few pages from the research paper ( ) tensor decomposition networks in a new neurips 2025 paper, yuchao lin and collaborators introduce tensor decomposition networks, showing how to significantly reduce the symmetry-related bottleneck with a far more efficient method with more than 2x the throughput while still maintaining accuracy. learn more ( ) a few pages from the research paper ( ) a vision-language model for spatial reasoning one of our neurips 2025 papers, co-authored by lambda researcher jianwen xie, introduces spatialreasoner, a vision-language model thatâ€™s equipped with explicit 3d representation and generalized 3d thinking for spatial reasoning. learn more ( ) a few pages from the research paper ( ) a benchmark for layout-to-image generation with dense overlaps lambda's jianwen xie and xiang zhang introduce overlaybench, a new approach to layout-to-image generation that leverages amodal masks during training. learn more ( ) a few pages from the research paper ( ) diffusion beats autoregressive in data-constrained settings in this latest neurips paper co-authored by lambda' amir zadeh, we show that masked diffusion models train for hundreds of epochs on the same corpus without overfitting, achieve lower validation loss and better downstream accuracy than autoregressive models, and exhibit a predictable compute threshold where they reliably pull ahead. learn more ( ) neurips bleuberi author amir zadeh ( ) rethinking reward models: bleu as a simple and effective proxy for llm alignment llm alignment typically relies on large and expensive reward models. what if a simple metric could replace them? in a new neurips 2025 paper, lambdaâ€™s amir zadeh and chuan li introduce bleuberi. learn more ( ) event.log() / webinar: building the next generation of ai factories ( ) webinar: building the next generation of ai factories with supermicro and lambda join maxx garrison and johnson eung to learn how lambda and supermicro solve the operational problems of modular, gpu-dense ai factories and validate the architecture, testing, and operational practices needed for mission-critical deployments. watch on demand ( ) youtube how to become a better reader in 2026 remembering rob reiner + how the open web can survive in the ai era (issue #408) how to become a better reader in 2026 remembering rob reiner + how the open web can survive in the ai era (issue #408) by the medium blog ( âˆ™ december 19, 2025 âˆ™ 4 min read âˆ™ view on medium ( years of scrolling have hijacked our attention spans, along with our ability to sit down and read a book. if reading more is on your 2026 resolutions list, here's some tested advice from avid readers to help you make the goal stick. despite being a former english teacher and literacy specialist, y.l. wolfe ( realized that her scrolling habit meant she'd barely finished a book in years. embarrassed by that realization, she agreed to read along with a friend's book club. she quickly found that reading on a regular schedule rebuilt her speed, focus, and ability to stay with a story ( . her best tips for rebuilding the habit: don't force yourself to finish a book you dislike, spend time sourcing books you will love, and be a little less precious about what you read but disciplined in making sure that you are reading regularly. once you start to enjoy reading again, you may as well get good at it. ryan holiday ( draws on decades of reading as a writer and bookstore owner to outline the habits good readers actually practice ( . he emphasizes strategies that help you build a reading life that compounds over time rather than chasing whatever happens to be newest-carrying a book so idle moments turn into reading time, and reading with a pen so ideas are processed, questioned, and retained. re-read books that matter. and let one book lead to another through footnotes, bibliographies, and recommendations. when you start reading constantly, you'll realize how hard it is to remember what you read. bobby powers ( should know: he's read over 700 books in the last 10 years. he describes a simple system he uses to keep track of ideas across these hundreds of books ( . as he reads, he stars passages he wants to return to and underlines only the lines that capture the core idea on a page. when he finishes a book, he writes a short index inside the back cover with page numbers, key takeaways, and related recommendations. by treating each book as a working document, powers creates something he can easily revisit instead of something that fades once the cover closes. - anna dorn ( ğŸ” medium reads for your weekend: if you're looking for book recommendations, barack obama ( just shared his list of favorite books, movies, and music from 2025 ( . for years, publishers on the open web have relied on advertising while platforms used their content to build much larger businesses. as generative ai becomes dominant, entrepreneur and wired co-founder john battelle ( sees publishers facing a familiar conundrum: make deals with the big platforms or try to develop a sustainable marketplace that lets them fairly value content - and build a healthier internet ( . sarah paris ( reflects on how rob reiner's films shaped her relationship to storytelling ( : the princess bride showed how a story could be sincere and hopeful without denying darkness; stand by me revealed that childhood fear, friendship, and longing were emotionally real and worth writing about; when harry met sally offered an early model for love built slowly through friendship and time. after a former boyfriend died suddenly at 53, karla l. miller ( revisits their years together, the moment she realized she wanted marriage and he didn't, and the breakup that followed. at his funeral, she reckons with what she lost, what she chose, and the unsettling truth that loving someone doesn't mean they were meant to be yours ( . after alzheimer's took away much of her father's independence, michele cambardella ( discovered that baking pizzelles-the traditional italian christmas cookies-was a ritual he could still perform by muscle memory ( . her lovely essay on making them with her father in the dining room of his assisted-living facility includes her family's time-tested recipe. ğŸ“º your weekly dose of practical wisdom about screen time "passive consumption (mindlessly scrolling or watching low-quality content) is associated with negative outcomes. interactive, educational, or creative screen use? often positive or neutral. social connection via screens? depends entirely on the quality of those connections." - psychologist constantin patrascu ( , arguing that the science on kids' screen time is far more nuanced ( than panic-driven headlines suggest. issue 308: software development time wasters mcp servers, imposter syndrome, and data centers in space ************* the overflow. ************* 17 december we've got a jampacked week for you of stories, so let's skip the small talk and get right to it. coming off microsoft ignite, we've got a look into how the enterprise is reframing their ai initiatives to be slower, steadier, and more focused on their market fit. if you didn't know, we debuted our rebrand and new mcp server at ignite, and if you're curious how that's all going, be sure to check out the interview we did with hp's distinguished technologist evan scheessele on how they're using our mcp server in their sdlc experiments. we also had a convo with salesforce's chief scientist and head of ai silvio savarese on how they're simulating terrible phone calls to make customer service ai agents better. okay, maybe we can have a little small talk. tell us, what do you hate about your job? we can guess...is it documentation? if it is, you're not aloneâ€”that's exactly what the data showed us in our latest stack overflow knows survey. but maybe you love documentation and hate code reviews. if so, we have a pod with macroscope's kayvon beykpour on how ai can ease some of your code review troubles. maybe all of our troubles would be erased if we could just get those pesky interfaces right; we have an episode with wesley yu from metalab on all things interfaces (which are everything, btw). all right, we're done with small talk now. let's have a deep discussion about the questions that matter the most. are wooden cutting boards more sanitary than plastic ones? what would it take to be a world-famous keynote speaker in software? why do programs and languages have such silly names? is your my 10 favorite books from the 70 books i read in 2025 view this post on the web at glaspâ€™s note: at glasp, we value the close personal relationships weâ€™ve built with thinkers, creators, and doers who fuel curiosity and growth. this week, we spotlight bobby powers [ ] â€”a lifelong learner passionate about leadership development and continuous improvement. with more than a decade of experience leading teams and developing learning and development at startups, bobby understands the transformative power of curiosity and mentorship. you might remember him from his glasp talk [ ] appearance, where he shared insights on leadership and personal growth, inspiring thousands. weâ€™re honored to continue learning from bobby and are thrilled to share his thoughtful reflections with our community. if you want to reread or highlight this newsletter, save it to glasp. glasp newsletter is a reader-supported publication. to receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber. hi glasp community! iâ€™m bobby powers, and i run the leader & learner publication [ ] on substack. i write two posts per week that will help you become a more curious leader and learner. for the past decade, iâ€™ve been reading at least 70 books per year. i love learning new things, so i read a lot of nonfiction, but i also enjoy fast-paced novels and literature. here were my 10 favorites from what i read in 2025. (note: my list is based on what i read this year, not what was published this year.) #10: a mystery of mysteries [ ] by mark dawidziak [ ] genre: nonfiction â†’ selective biography of edgar allan poe i had no idea how much mystery surrounded edgar allan poeâ€™s death. on october 3, 1849, poe was found semiconscious in baltimore. he was wearing someone elseâ€™s cheap, shabby clothes (no one knows whose). his hat was soiled (and also belonged to someone else). he was raving and incoherent (some witnesses thought from alcohol but others disagreed). and no one knew where he had been for the past week (the last time someone saw him was september 26 in richmond). a friend came and tried to nurse poe back to health, but he was dead within the week. he died the morning of october 7th, and the day before his death, he supposedly called out for someone named â€œreynoldsâ€ (but scholars still donâ€™t know who that was). historians still debate poeâ€™s cause of death. crazy. poeâ€™s death seems like a story that came from his pen, but he also led a pretty crazy life. he had massive public feuds with multiple friends and authors. he fabricated much of his lifeâ€™s story and fed fictional morsels about himself to the press. and he also fell in love with his 13-year-old first cousin virginia and married her, but scholars still question the nature of their relationship. youâ€™re probably familiar with some of poeâ€™s poems like â€œthe ravenâ€ and short stories like â€œthe tell-tale heartâ€ and â€œthe fall of the house of usher.â€ but iâ€™m guessing youâ€™re less familiar with the fact that he was also an esteemed (and controversial) literary critic who enjoyed blasting his peersâ€™ work in magazines. poe led an interesting life, and this book covers the highlights without getting lost in uninteresting details. unlike many biographies, a mystery of mysteries [ ] is less than 300 pages, so even if youâ€™re not a big biography person, youâ€™ll enjoy it. #9: a christmas carol [ ] by charles dickens [ ] genre: fiction â†’ classic literature, holidays, heart-warming before this year, i had seen multiple versions of the movie but never read the book. (btw, if you havenâ€™t seen it before, go watch the 1992 disney classic the muppet christmas carol. it holds up.) i debated whether i wanted to read the book because i already knew the story, but iâ€™m glad i did. itâ€™s a quick read (~100 pages), well worth an hour or two of your time. dickensâ€™s visceral storytelling will induce you to hate scrooge before his conversion and make you want to hug him afterward. a christmas carol [ ] is so iconic because it captures the power of gratitude, selflessness, and kindnessâ€”all qualities we could use more of in the world today. #8: the let them theory [ ] by mel robbins [ ] genre: nonfiction â†’ personal development, psychology i donâ€™t know how many copies this book sold, but i saw it everywhere in 2025. iâ€™m often skeptical of mega-bestsellers, but iâ€™m glad i picked up a copy because i got a lot out of this book. the let them theory is definitely not a perfect book: itâ€™s repetitive. it could have been a bit shorter without losing the message. and itâ€™s basically a modern-day repackaging of ancient stoic wisdom like â€œonly focus on what you can control and forget about everything else.â€ but strangely enough, those are the same reasons why i enjoyed this book. robbinsâ€™s repetition of the core themes helped me understand the problem from various perspectives. by articulating the same point with stories from various realms of life, she pounded the idea into my head. plus, this book is much easier to read than most works of philosophy and wisdom, which makes it a great gateway book for anyone who wants to dabble in philosophy. the let them theory [ ] doesnâ€™t have the depth of seneca or epictetus, but thatâ€™s why a lot of people love it. itâ€™s a manual for living life on your own terms and ignoring the haters. #7: 11/22/63 [ ] by stephen king [ ] genre: fiction â†’ mystery, thriller, time travel, popular fiction i donâ€™t enjoy many time travel stories because they tend to be confusing and overly sentimental, so when a couple of my friends recommended stephen kingâ€™s time travel book 11/22/63 [ ], i was skeptical. king is my favorite novelist, but i still didnâ€™t know if the book would be my thing. thankfully, i was wrong. iâ€™ve read 30 of kingâ€™s books, and this one quickly became one of my favorites. in typical fashion, king crafts a brilliant story, paints compelling characters, and also gives you a couple of hateable villains. the story swirls around english teacher jake epping, who learns of a portal to the past from his dying friend al. al has spent years researching the lives of john f. kennedy and lee harvey oswald to figure out how to go back in time to prevent jfkâ€™s assassination. just before al dies, he enlists jake in his cause. what made me love this book is that itâ€™s so much more than a â€œgo back in time to prevent a bad thingâ€ story. itâ€™s a story about love, loss, sacrifice, and more. read this book if youâ€™re looking for a great, suspenseful storyâ€”but buckle up for a long ride because the book is nearly 900 pages. ;-) #6: book and dagger [ ] by elyse graham [ ] genre: nonfiction â†’ history, world war ii, spycraft did you know that in wwii, the u.s. recruited librarians and college professors as spies against germany and the axis powers? pretty crazy! they chose bookish nerds for the task because they tended to be smart, well-read, and unassuming. i loved this book because it not only taught me about wwii but also about spycraft: how countries research their enemies, trap them into believing false information, and find helpful war intel in everyday publications like newspapers and magazines. book and dagger [ ] is one of the most fun historical books iâ€™ve ever read. if youâ€™re a nerd (like me) who wants to feel like james bond, read this book. #5: dark squares [ ] by danny rensch [ ] genre: nonfiction â†’ memoir, chess, cults, entrepreneurship if your eyes skimmed past the line in italics above, re-read it. yep, all of those topics are covered in this book. i grew up playing in chess tournaments, so this book hit hard for me. but itâ€™ll also hit hard for you if youâ€™re interested in learning more about cult psychology or trauma. rensch grew up in a cult in arizona. when he was nine years old, he learned how to play chess and got really good, really fast. once cult leader steven kamp noticed renschâ€™s aptitude for chess, he took rensch away from his mom and organized his entire life around the game. although it covers some dismal ground, dark squares [ ] is ultimately a hopeful book. rensch worked through much of his brainwashing, family trauma, and alcoholism to become a capable, functioning adult, and he later co-founded chess.com, the largest chess site on the planet. #4: dungeon crawler carl [ ] by matt dinniman [ ] genre: fiction â†’ fantasy, gaming, light-hearted i donâ€™t read much fantasy, but this one blew me away. dungeon crawler carl [ ] is a fun, rollicking ride through a dystopian earth thatâ€™s been conquered by aliens. carl and his ex-girlfriendâ€™s cat princess donut struggle to survive while the universe watches on intergalactic tv. this book appeals to gamers because it references a bunch of video game lingo and archetypes. but iâ€™m not even a gamer, and i loved it because the characters are hilarious and the writing is cheekily brilliant. if you check out this book, i highly recommend the audiobook. jeff hays is the best narrator iâ€™ve ever heard. #3: six thinking hats [ ] by edward de bono [ ] genre: nonfiction â†’ business, leadership, decision-making, meetings six thinking hats ended up being so good that i instantly added it to my list of the books iâ€™d require company leaders to read if i start a business someday (along with modern classics like patrick lencioniâ€™s death by meeting [ ], cal newportâ€™s deep work [ ], and erin meyerâ€™s the culture map [ ]). de bono says we have a problem in western culture: we focus too much on debate when making decisions. rather than digging in our heels and arguing for â€œour side,â€ he encourages leaders to evaluate any important decision from six different angles, as explained in the image below. i donâ€™t expect you to get as nerdily excited about decision-making models as i do. but this bookâ€™s principles can help you evaluate choices in your own life, like deciding whether to leave your job, move to a different state, or start your own business. #2: building a story brand [ ] by donald miller [ ] genre: nonfiction â†’ business, marketing, storytelling, positioning building a story brand [ ] is essentially â€œthe heroâ€™s journeyâ€ for marketers. miller shows that the story structure behind blockbuster movies and award-winning tv series can also be harnessed by anyone trying to sell a product or service. from star wars to itâ€™s a wonderful life, this seven-part framework reigns supreme: â€œhere is nearly every story you see or hear in a nutshell: a character who wants something encounters a problem before they can get it. at the peak of their despair, a guide steps into their lives, gives them a plan, and calls them to action. that action helps them avoid failure and ends in a success.â€ -donald miller this book helped me revamp my website, change how iâ€™m pitching my public speaking services, and rethink how i position myself on social media. iâ€™ve read a ton of marketing books, but this one is the best. thereâ€™s a good reason itâ€™s sold over one million copies. #1: die with zero [ ] by bill perkins [ ] genre: nonfiction â†’ personal finance, retirement, living a good life die with zero [ ] is one of the most practical yet countercultural books iâ€™ve ever read. itâ€™s the personal finance book i didnâ€™t realize i needed. for years, iâ€™ve read about the power of compounding interest and the importance of saving while youâ€™re young. perkins agrees with those concepts (he is a hedge fund manager, after all), but he also poses some fascinating contrary questions: what happens if you save a bunch of money but die early? or what if you arenâ€™t healthy enough later in life to gallivant around and spend the money youâ€™ve hoarded? in short, what if youâ€™re saving too much? i loved this book because it flies in the face of most personal finance advice, yet i found myself nodding along as i read the core principles of every chapter. perkins tells emotional stories, brings relevant data, and logically explains each point. by the end of the book, i was so convinced by his arguments that i immediately made a couple of big financial changes in my life. what were your favorite reads this year? iâ€™m always looking for recommendations (and i know other readers are too), so drop a comment below! btw, if youâ€™re interested in receiving two posts per week with book recs and personal development tips, iâ€™d be honored for you to subscribe to leader & learner. image splitting, corner-shape tags, and a view transitions debug view this issue on codepen image splitting, corner-shape tags, and a view transitions debug today's codepen community highlights include a trippy image splitter with glassy, mirror-like reflections from amit sheen, a cool css trick for cutting out a classic price tag shape with corner-shape from mark thomes, and an in-depth debugging of blinking view transitions from miguel pimentel for piccalilli. pen image splitter amit sheen shares a cool tool for splitting an image into glassy, chunky pixels. upload your pic, mess around with the sliders, and download your new image when you like what you see. pen baubles view "these interesting reflections were created using three render passes. i imagined a slightly faded photograph of a colourfully decorated christmas tree. i wanted to capture this mood and the texture of the old photograph in this shader. therefore, i lightened the darkest black to a darker grey and added a strong vignette around the scene." from matthias hurrle. collection #codepenchallenge: cozy winter in the 2nd week of our winter wonderland challenge, we settled into a cozy winter. check out our collection from week two, including pens by chris bolson , matt cannon , vanessa victorino , and gemma croad . want to join the winter fun? the final challenge of 2025 is on now ! link creating a liquid glass distortion effect with webgl and glsl shaders get a detailed look at how lichingchester created this intense text distortion effect in this detailed tutorial, suitable for front-end devs with some three.js experience. pen corner-shape - price tag mark thomes cuts out a classic price tag shape with the new corner-shape shorthand property, combining the round and bevel values to cut those corners. sponsor build modern apps faster with atlas the new era of ai demands a database built for continuous change and global scale. mongodb atlas is ai-ready with native vector search, and it can be deployed in over 125+ regions worldwide to meet your most demanding workload needs. build ai apps faster, all in one place. pen css zoom resize alvaro montoro shares a cool css trick! " this is a static flat image created with css gradients. resize the window. it will look like the card is moving closer or farther away. if you remove the card, it will look like the background expands horizontally, but it doesn't necessarily move back/forth (even with the perspective)." link pausing a css animation with getanimations() cassidy williams shares a quick tutorial on how to use the getanimations() method to pause a css animation, complete with a pen so you can try it yourself! pen why are my view transitions blinking? at piccalilli, miguel pimentel shares what he learned from spending "more time than iâ€™d like to admit debugging view transitions blinks" so you don't have to make the same mistakes. work along with the pen of the broken version , or learn from the fixed pen ! pen postcard from lanzarote a lovely css greeting from mads stoumann! "saw this bath-towel today, and re-created it with shape() and a palette of the wonderful colors of cÃ©sar manrique, lanzarote's most famous artist." chrisâ€™ corner a collection of web design and development news and thoughts from codepen's own chris coyier. cloud four this is an appreciation post for the cloud four blog . itâ€™s one of those must-subscribes. i find myself adding almost every post they put out to my archive of posts to dig into. so since iâ€™m overflowing with them a bit, and there is a hot-off-the-presses one, i figured iâ€™d share that and a bunch of favorites. in responsive letter spacing , tyler sticka covers a scenario where you want to tighten up letter-spacing, but be smart about it. at big font sizes, some tightening looks good (i put it on my own starter ) but at smaller font sizes, it harms readability. using em is a good start as it scales with the font size automatically, but then itâ€™s better to reduce it as it gets smaller. fortunately tyler found a great way to do it with clamp() . * { letter-spacing: clamp( -0.05em, calc((1em - 1rem) / -10), 0em ); } great minds think alike as i was thinking about the ui/ux pattern of one-time password inputs lately too. tyler again here tackles it his own way in simple one-time passcode inputs . we agree: donâ€™t actually make it multiple <input /> elements, as tempting as that is from a styling perspective. there is simply too much javascript required to make that work nicely (which can easily break down) and you otherwise get for free if you donâ€™t do that. instead, use the proper set of attributes on an input for it: <input type="text" inputmode="numeric" autocomplete="one-time-code" maxlength="6" /> then just style it with css to make it look however you want. that is, apply the input mask with styles alone . i was just bemoaning the loss of jpeg xl the other day, but in on container queries, responsive images, and jpeg-xl a couple years back, jason grigsby was already in grief. container queries, one of the great css revelations of our time, is spiritually connected to responsive images in that they want to do the most-appropriate thing with the information available on how they are displayed on the page. youâ€™d think they would get along and share information, but youâ€™d be wrong. we could evolve the syntaxes to help, and probably should, but itâ€™s intereseting that jpeg-xl, and image format , was actually somewhat designed to help with this and would have been a serendipitous gift for web developers, if we actually were able to use it. speaking of images, i think we all know weâ€™re not really supposed to be using gif anymore as the performance sucks and we can replicate it with video. i tend to like the video approach, but there are significant drawbacks to be aware of: colin bendell pointed out that browsers donâ€™t preload video , which can impact perceived performance. by default, the video experience isnâ€™t very gif-like: you need a magic combination of autoplay , loop , muted and playsinline attributes to achieve similar behavior. the video element exposes more playback control possibilities, which can be good for accessibility, but it lacks an alt attribute for alternative text. (the title and fallback content donâ€™t seem to be exposed to assistive devices in a similar way, but maybe aria-label or aria-labelledby would work?) tyler looked at alternatives and there are some really strong contenders in the form of newfangled image formats. but (surprise surprise) the browser support story is dicey. gerardo rodriguez talks about testing html light dom web components: easier than expected! good to know, really. testing here meaning load up the component in a browser-like environment and make sure what you expect to be there in the dom is there and interacting with it does what you expect. itâ€™s not like you canâ€™t test web components that use the shadow dom, but in practice itâ€™s an annoying barrier that you have to manually account for in many places, and other tools need to be aware of and work with as well. nice to have so much example code here to reference. ok fine one more. this is a nice demo of a common web app interaction. itâ€™s a good reminder that we really need to implement â€œbulk actionsâ€ in more places on codepen properly. you can adjust your email preferences any time, or instantly opt out of emails of this kind. need help with anything? hit up support . interested in sponsoring? here's our sponsorship info .

a letter from tony stubblebine, medium ceo hi there, this is tony stubblebine, ceo of medium. i'm writing to thank you for becoming a medium member. i'd like to share a clearer sense of what we're trying to do, why it matters, and how to make the most of your membership. we believe that everyone has a story to tell. on medium, anyone can share insightful perspectives, useful knowledge, and life wisdom with the world. each story has a chance to influence others, plant a seed, perhaps even start a movement. we do our best to help these stories find the audience they deserve and help readers find stories that move them, through a system based on human curation and member-driven engagement. as a result, over 100 million people read and connect on medium every month. this is why medium exists: to spread human-centric, human-created ideas that deepen our understanding of the world. medium is creating not just a platform, but a new information ecosystem-one that's open for everyone to participate in, and rewards quality over quantity. one that values diverse perspectives and doesn't allow hate, harassment, or intolerance. one that spreads important ideas and sparks intelligent conversations. when you read and write on medium, you're contributing to a global community that values depth, nuance, and substantive storytelling that wouldn't be possible anywhere else. so, how do you get the most out of your membership? open medium ( , and find your favorite writers ( . discover your favorite corners of medium: start with our staff picks ( , or follow a topic ( . read a story. highlight a sentence or two (or browse your past highlights ( ). find a publication about the ideas you're most passionate about, independently run by editors who share that passion. if you're feeling inspired, leave a response. add stories you love into lists ( . even better, write your own story ( . start your own publication! build your reading lists, your followers, your knowledge base, your medium community. we're glad you're here. we have come a long way on this journey, but we're just getting started. as a paying member, you're critical to our mission. at any time, feel free to reply to this email to share your thoughts with our team. thank you for reading, tony stubblebine ceo, medium read from anywhere. sent by medium ( Â·3500 south dupont highway, suite iq-101, dover, de 19901 unsubscribe ( from this type of emailÂ·careers ( Â·help center ( Â·privacy policy ( Â·terms of service (

giving better gifts is all about intention the power of soft skills in business + will ai destroy healthcare? (issue #407) giving better gifts is all about intention the power of soft skills in business + will ai destroy healthcare? (issue #407) by the medium blog ( âˆ™ december 12, 2025 âˆ™ 4 min read âˆ™ view on medium ( the annual holiday shopping scramble hits everyone differently - some dread shopping for large families, some are looking for honest reviews, and others want to skip conventional consumerism entirely. whether you're overwhelmed or excited to start, medium has resources to make holiday gift-giving easier and more intentional. for parents facing the annual chaos of shopping for multiple generations, bebe nicholson ( has the hack for you. after years of hosting three adult children, their spouses, and 12 grandchildren, she couldn't buy unique gifts for every age and personality. so she created a christmas grab bag of more than 30 wrapped presents ranging from framed greek art to bags of m&m's ( : starting with the youngest, everyone picks two gifts, then they trade until everyone's satisfied. for the rightfully overwhelmed parents, patrickmh ( captures the madness with his humorous guide to surviving the season (#97cd) . he serves gammon roasted in coca-cola, pizza on christmas day because that's what makes his kids happy, and christmas crackers to maintain tradition. there are dozens of specialty publications on medium that can help you find the right things for the special people in your life. for the techies, mac o'clock ( reviews whether apple products are worth your money (spoiler: the iphone 17 pro isn't). for the backpackers and commuters, pangolins with packs ( compiles backpack reviews from three self-proclaimed backpack addicts. bricks n'brackets ( breaks down all things related to lego (they loved the new ford bronco technic set ( ). for the generalists, casual product reviews ( covers everything from fitbod to voice dictation software. for the always-hungry, casual snack reviews ( (started, like casual product reviews, by some folks here at medium) weighs in on things like exotic popcorn ( and the best snack for a bike ride. speaking of bikes, medium product designer sophie aguado ( found the perfect gift for workout enthusiasts: a folding bike ( that lets her ride before and after her train commute, easily her best purchase of 2025. for the bookworms in your life, bethany f. brengan ( 's bookish gift guide ( spans free printable bookmarks to a tree-shaped bookshelf to miniature typewriters. and for those rethinking holiday consumption entirely, tariana ( 's anti-capitalist gift guide ( advocates for homemade gifts and personalized wrapping over convenience shopping. her list of intentional gifts includes: scrapbooks for the sentimental friend, custom clothing with inside jokes for significant others, and burned cds for the cool grandparents who still have a player. also mindful of consumerist waste, maria cassano ( argues that experiences bring more joy than stuff ( . her list of non-physical gifts includes masterclass subscriptions, local adventures found on tripadvisor, spa gift cards, psychic readings, and even therapy sessions for those who've expressed interest. for more eco-friendly options ( , anne r. greenberg ( suggests diy infused liquor kits made with air-fryer dehydrated fruit and spices in mason jars, noting that household waste increases by more than 25% from thanksgiving to new year's. if a living gift is more your style, carol labuzzetta, ms ( suggests amaryllis bulbs ( as foolproof gifts that bloom in january - everything the plant needs for a year is in the bulb. whether it's objects, experiences, or time, mindful giving is what makes the holidays meaningful. -anna dorn ( other stories from across medium for your weekend reading: iryna nozdrin ( spent a decade as a community pharmacist, handing prenatal vitamins to new moms and consoling grieving relatives. but now with ai poised to start taking on the role of clinicians, the biggest threat she sees isn't job replacement, it's these systems scaling pre-existing biases ( like forcing patients to be discharged too early, all while cutting out human (and humane) care. when organizational psychiatrist david evan "daven" morrison m.d. ( advises senior executives, they often ask him to deliver critical messages they're afraid to share themselves, saying "i don't have your soft skills." morrison explores why executives dismiss emotions and interpersonal dynamics as "soft stuff" ( while respecting terms like "basis points" and "shareholder value." he argues that when people ridicule soft skills or make jokes about therapy, it reveals the group's discomfort with vulnerability - and often signals something important the organization isn't addressing. stop trying to make your notebook "perfect." ( shalveena rohde ( 's first attempt at a creative idea journal failed because she wrote only what she thought she should, leaving out her own thoughts and sketches. on her second try, she filled it with whatever inspired her - doodles, goals, favorite passages - and even built a digital version that keeps her handwriting and lets her edit freely. now it's a notebook she can't stop returning to. anyone who's lost a loved one knows the ache of remembering them as they were, and then watching them fade into someone you barely recognize. kelley jhung ( had watched her father slip away to dementia, losing pieces of himself day by day. on his birthday, she revisited the days she cared for him - feeding him, reading his letters, laughing at his jokes, celebrating his small triumphs. by reliving these moments, he came alive again in her memory ( , proud and teasing, returned through stories, memories, and words. ğŸ your weekly highlight about gift-giving: "a gift exchange is an acknowledgment that we are with each other in the world, a little gesture of understanding that, simply, we may help each other." a quote by ecologist carl safina, from paul greenberg ( 's story about how true gifting is about giving time and attention ( , rather than just stuff. on the 31st! if you're practicing your numbers in preparation for the new years' countdown, we're right there with you. we're counting down the top ten stack overflow blogs of 2025, and this week we've got the first five for your holiday reading pleasure. from popping the ai bubble to the ick you get from slop to the losing employment battle gen z is having against bots, this year's blogs dug deep into the economic, cultural, and technical shifts caused by ai in 2025. and don't worry, we wrote about stuff besides ai. rounding out the first five of our countdown are the great unracking of our last physical datacenter, and a piece on making your codebase better by making your code coverage worse. if you're in more of a listening mood, you're in luck because the pod stops for no holiday. we're joined by former stack overflow board member anil dash for a conversation on how ai is normal and should be treated as such. we also spoke with dan ciruli from nutanix about the delicate dance between vms and kubernetes in cloud-native environments. from around the web, we've got a piece on when we can expect quantum computing to be scalable (apparently it's imminent), one dev's reflection on a year of vibe coding, plus the disproving of the old developer proverb, "if you're as clever as you can be when you write your code, how will you ever debug it?" wait, is that 2026 i see on the horizon? let's countdown the end of this issue the way we always doâ€”with some questions. 5...what would aristotle say about cliff's notes? 4...will people believe me if i say the reason i don't everything you need to know is right here! choose your niche - standing out by standing for something you know what a niche is - like most people. but most people donâ€™t know what having a niche does. a tight niche does 3 things: ğŸ”¸signals expertise:readers and algorithms reward depth over breadth; they trust specialists who solve a clear, repeatable problem. ğŸ”¸accelerates creativity: constraints force fresh angles. develop your perspectives, grow your knowledge, and dissect one new regulation each week rather than recapping tech news in general. ğŸ”¸builds a magnet audience: people come back when they know what they will get and how it will help them next time. so, how do you choose your niche? ğŸ”¸ inventory your intersections: make a habit of ideation - list 10 topics you can discuss for an hour each, then cross-match with 10 problems your ideal reader faces. the overlaps are where passion meets market demand. ğŸ”¸run the "5-article test": draft five headlines inside one overlap. if ideas flow easily, and you're still curious after the fifth - you have a sustainable lane. ğŸ”¸stake a pov statement: do your research and find out one thing most people in your niche often ignore. pin it, read further into it, and voila - youâ€™ve got something to analyze. voice follows focus. when you know exactly why you're writing and for whom, word choice, metaphors, and structure start to feel inevitable. and when you do explore new territory? your established voice travels with you, making even departures feel intentional. this is also the beauty of owning your niche and having your own voice. when you do want to experiment, i.e., test a new format, explore an adjacent field, or share a personal story, you're not starting from zero. your audience trusts you enough to follow. ready to take all of the above into action? everything around you is taking their own subtle shifts. and just like how the weather changes and the leaves start to fall, the world of technology is no different. on the blog, our ceo prashanth chandrasekar writes about one of those shifts in technologyâ€”how success is measured in a post gen-ai world. and in a post gen-ai world, the shift in technology seems to feel distinctly agentic. guillaume de saint marc from outshift by cisco joined us on the pod to talk about the future of multi-agent frameworks and what kind of infrastructure needs to be built for it. speaking of agent infrastructure, on leaders of code, our very own ben matthews sat down with postman's abhinav asthana to talk apis in the ai era. plus, this week, we're introducing our own agentâ€”ai assist, a new way to access the 17 years of expert knowledge living on stack overflow. even as the seasons change, some things remain trueâ€”traditional rss feeds are boring, people love free movies, and code is only as good as the humans who are working on it. we have all three of those stories around the web for you this week, plus one on why finance bros should now fear ai taking their jobs like the rest of us. oh, and another truth that remains true: robots are pretty cool. we were joined by viam's vp of engineering, simone kalmakis, to explore how abstraction is making those very cool robots
